HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1344
By Atchley
A RESOLUTION to honor the legendary Dolly Parton on the
occasion of a segment of U.S. Highway 411 and
U.S. Highway 25W being named in her honor.
WHEREAS, Dolly Parton is Tennessee's most beloved and accomplished native
daughter, a supremely gifted and multi-talented writer, entertainer, and businesswoman whose
compassionate spirit is at the heart of all she does and whose philanthropy has touched the
lives of millions around the world; and
WHEREAS, an international ambassador for Tennessee's music, culture, and values,
Dolly Paton has committed her life to charity, education, economic development, and
community service, through which she has had a profound and lasting impact on Tennesseans,
this country, and the world; and
WHEREAS, Dolly Parton has brought joy and hope to all who love and admire her; she
is an inspiration throughout the world, especially in her home of East Tennessee, to which she
has remained devoted throughout her life; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Parton's ever-growing legacy is one that lands her firmly among the
pantheon of country music greats, but beyond that, she is an exemplar most worthy of
emulation—a shining example of the difference one person can make through hard work and
compassionate action; and
WHEREAS, this General Assembly has passed legislation to designate a segment of
U.S. Highway 411 and U.S. Highway 25W in Sevier and Cocke counties as the "Dolly Parton
Parkway"; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should recognize Dolly Parton on this special occasion;
now, therefore,
HJR1344
017616
- 1 -

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that on the occasion of a segment of U.S. Highway 411 and U.S. Highway 25W
being named in her honor, we pay tribute to Dolly Parton for her many cultural, civic, and
philanthropic contributions to Tennessee and to the world.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
